year 1988 saw elections in both the United States and Canada. It also saw a turning point in the tenor of television campaign advertising. By the early 1990s there was a growing reliance upon negative political images and symbols. This book is about that growing reliance. While focusing on the use of “attack” ads, Television Advertising in Canadian Elections provides a historical overview of the growth of negative advertising. It includes a discussion of advertisers’ intentions and strategies, an analysis of the ads played on both English language and French television and their impact and the ethics of political advertising. This is the first book-length investigation of negative political advertising in Canada. Professional politicians, as well as anyone interested in election politics, journalism, communication studies or advertising, will find this an absorbing study.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAdvertising, PoliticalxCanada. 0aAdvertising, PoliticalzCanada. 0aNegativismxCanada. 0aNegativism. 0aTelevision in politicsxCanada. 0aTelevision in politicszCanada. 4aFilm & Media. 4aPolitical Science. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Communication Studies.2bisacsh1 aCarney, T. F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCunningham, Stanley B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCunningham, Stanley B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGill, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGosselin, André, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHildebrandt, Kai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLebel, Estelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRomanow, Walter I., econtributor.4ctb4h